up of a locally compact group to a unitary representation of the whole group. Later a parallel construction using complex analysis and its associated co-homology theories grew up as a result of work by Borel, Weil, Harish-Chandra, Bott, Langlands, Kostant, and Schmid. Cohomological induction, introduced by Zuckerman, is an algebraic analog that is technically more manageable than the complex-analysis construction and leads to a large repertory of irreducible unitary representations of reductive Lie groups. The book, which is accessible to students beyond the first year of graduate school, will interest mathematicians and physicists who want to learn about and take advantage of the algebraic side of the representation theory of Lie groups. Cohomological Induction and Unitary Representations develops the necessary background in representation theory and includes an introductory chapter of motivation, a thorough treatment of the "translation principle," and four appendices on algebra and analysis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aHarmonic analysis. 0aHomology theory. 0aRepresentations of groups. 0aSemisimple Lie groups. 7aMATHEMATICS / Algebra / Abstract.2bisacsh  aAbelian category.  aAdditive identity.  aAdjoint representation.  aAlgebra homomorphism.  aAssociative algebra.  aAssociative property.  aAutomorphic form.  aAutomorphism.  aBanach space.  aBasis (linear algebra).  aBilinear form.  aCartan pair.  aCartan subalgebra.  aCartan subgroup.  aCayley transform.  aCharacter theory.  aClassification theorem.  aCohomology.  aCommutative property.  aComplexification (Lie group).  aComposition series.  aConjugacy class.  aConjugate transpose.  aDiagram (category theory).  aDimension (vector space).  aDirac delta function.  aDiscrete series representation.  aDol